  "event_preview": "Oxford Plains Speedway is a 0.375-mile (0.604 km) paved oval in Oxford, Maine, opened in 1950 and operating in its current configuration since a 1992 repaving and backstretch widening that expanded the layout from its original third-mile dimensions. The track seats 14,000 — the largest capacity of any sporting venue in Maine. The All States Materials Group 150 marks the first Whelen Modified Tour visit to Oxford in 35 years, with the series having previously raced here five times in the mid-1980s through the early 1990s, the last occasion being June 1991 when future Tour champion Jeff Fuller won. Previous Whelen Modified Tour winners at the Route 26 oval include NASCAR Hall of Famer Richie Evans, former Cup Series winner Jimmy Spencer, and longtime Xfinity Series standout Mike McLaughlin. The race is Race 4 of the 2026 season and runs 150 laps (56.25 miles).\n\nThe absence of four-time champion and 48-time series winner Justin Bonsignore — who has withdrawn along with confirming he will also skip the following Seekonk event — means the field will race without him for the first time since October 2009. Bonsignore sits fifth in the championship standings, having won the season opener at New Smyrna before finishing seventh at Thompson. Patrick Emerling, who leads the entry list in the No. 1, is among the pre-event favourites; Ron Silk and Matt Hirschman complete the strongest of the remaining contingent.\n\nBecause the Whelen Modified Tour has not visited Oxford in 35 years, all qualifying and race lap records at the circuit will be set for the first time this weekend in the series' modern era.",
